The paper deals with game theory and cooperative games, which are typically classified under cs.GT (Game Theory). The concept of $k$-additive core involves combinatorial aspects, which could also fall under cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The paper also discusses the use of sharing rules to derive classical imputations from $k$-order imputations, which could be related to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the preservation of coalitional rationality in the $k$-additive core could be relevant to social choice theory, which is often classified under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
